\section*{Health Information System, Vision, Mission \& Goal}
- Vision: Be a center of excellence for quality health and health related data and information for use by all.
- Goal: To generate and use health information for policy formulation, management, planning, budgeting, implementation, monitoring and evaluation of health services and programme interventions in the health sector
- Mission (Purpose): To provide timely, reliable and accessible quality health service information for evidence based decision making in order to maximize utilization of scarce resources in the health sector.

\section*{Broad objectives of HIS}
1. To generate/provide data/ information (qualitative and quantitative) quality and timely required for planning, M\&E, efficient management of health services and decision making.
2. To facilitate/help information dissemination, feedback (horizontal and vertical) and use of information for evidence based decision making.
3. To create and maintain health information data base.
4. To create an open, continuous dialogue between those who collect and users of information with the aim of improving health services.
5. To determine end user information needs at the various levels of the health system.

\section*{Advantages of a functional HIS}
a. Information is readily available when requested or required, avoiding the last minute rush to look for data.
b. Policy makers and managers of programs use the information for health and development planning and implementation and are sensitized on importance and effective utilization of information
c. Resource mobilization and allocation. Once data is readily available it is easy to project the required resources by extrapolating from the past trends with a fairly good accuracy. Rule of the thumb should not be norm or the practice.
d. Monitoring trends: Disease surveillance is functional and it is thus easy to predict the occurrence of epidemics of diseases.
e. Problems and gap identification: Various departments and institutions becomes part of the system; there is collaboration and coordination among various actors.
f. The work and duties of the staff that are involved in the system is appreciated and recognized.
g. Ad hoc surveys and consultancies are avoided.
h. Decision making and priority service setting.
i. Operational research and training becomes easy and enables quick retrieval of the evidences in practice and use evidence based practices for demonstration.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_11_18_7794677cee204c34483ag-13.jpg?height=112&width=375&top_left_y=2569&top_left_x=875)
j. Monitoring and evaluation of projects and programs will be made easier and alongside working corrective measures or change of strategies will be realized in the initial stages.
k. Donor influence in HMIS is also avoided as in case of reviews.

